  "textBoxes": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "x": 10,
      "y": -470,
      "w": 620,
      "h": 40,
      "text": "Title: Inductor Basics — Ramp, Kickback, Choke",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "x": 10,
      "y": -428,
      "w": 1060,
      "h": 46,
      "text": "Description: Three coil mini-demos: current that ramps instead of jumping, a flyback kick caught by a freewheel LED, and an RL choke that smothers a blinking clock.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "x": 10,
      "y": -360,
      "w": 420,
      "h": 180,
      "text": "1. COILS RESIST CHANGE IN CURRENT\nFlip the switch. The red LED (plain resistor) snaps on instantly. The green LED sits behind a 47mH coil, so its current has to ramp up — it fades in over a couple of seconds. Once the ramp finishes, the coil acts like a plain wire (LEDs equally bright): at DC an inductor is just a wire.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "x": 450,
      "y": -360,
      "w": 420,
      "h": 180,
      "text": "2. FLYBACK KICKBACK\nHold the button a few seconds to let current build in the coil, then RELEASE. The current has nowhere to go, so the coil slams its left node negative — and the yellow freewheel LED (wired from GND up to the coil) catches that kick and flashes while the stored energy drains. This is why relay coils always get a flyback diode.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "x": 890,
      "y": -360,
      "w": 420,
      "h": 180,
      "text": "3. RL CHOKE (FILTER)\nThe 2Hz clock drives two identical LED branches. The red LED blinks hard. The green one sits behind a coil: the current never gets going before the clock flips again, so the blink is smothered to a dim throb. A coil passes DC but fights fast changes — that's a choke.",
      "v": 2
    }
  ]
}
